@8Rider6 Perhaps I am naive, though my education is in history and government, my career was heavily involved in administrative law I am not an attorney and have very little experience with criminal law. That said I do think our criminal system could use a shakeup The social and restorative justice neo-Marxists have been far too successful in reducing the risk of committing a crime. This has over the past few decades this idea of oppressed and therefore guiltless groups has spread and the ideas of Marcuse have spread from universities to grade schools from economics and law to history and teacher education. 

There have always been some corrupt judges and some overtly partisan judges and some incompetent judges. We the people elect them or the people who appoint them and we the people can reform them, but what usually happens is we vote the same old same old and the express outrage when something goes wrong.

I live in a small town, I can meet with the mayor or the council members or the staff if I make the effort. I can attend and speak at council meetings, and I have done so several times. Quite often the council and staff outnumber the people in the audience. In all of the town's existence no council member has ever been recalled and only one lost an election because of well-founded evidence of corruption. But most people most of the time pay no attention to how the town is governed. As we go up to higher levels the disconnect is even greater. There is no chance of my meeting a Senator and my Representative will fob me off on one of his staff. Perhaps there is an upper limit to a well functioning representative government.

